A Republican Strategy to Oppose Obama's Re-election
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to fight election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by confirming that voter fraud in the U.S. is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning strikes.
By the way, in 10 years, Republicans’ lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for the conduct of elections in individual states.
In this sense, the majority of U.S. governments have since 2009 promulgated new laws that make the registration or entry procedure more difficult.
This phenomenon has gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were able to be registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time limits for early voting, declare the right to be invalid to register as a voter on election day, and provide citizens with the right to vote for which a court act exists.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible people, do not have a government-issued photo ID card issued by their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a designation.
However, you often have to pay more than a hundred dollars to get the required ID.
Young people, minorities and people with low incomes are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with incomes of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are considered voters who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs to choose more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by those clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws that require voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic voices.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011 Republican lawmakers in eight states sponsored laws that abolished voter registration on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns for voter registration in the 2004 general election have helped to register approximately 10 million citizens.
As a result of the measures adopted since 2009, the share of registration of new voters in 2010 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the time frame for early voting in the state.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who had voted in advance were African-Americans, although they make up only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same goes for the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, whites, representing 76% of voters, accounted for only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to enforce the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics are striking at the partisan nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear objective the influence of the results in the countries that decide for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that have passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the legislation on the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
