The Higgs Boson Analyzes
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has sparked a bit of a stir last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "at least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but empirically has not yet been observed.
But for physicists, it’s still not entirely certain that it’s really about the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure about it.
However, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of being fooled, and let’s look at what it’s all about.
In this world, there is a necessarily inevitable law that causes two objects to not be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard as you will get hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that for them there is also such a law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state", and are in the same "great state", and in this "great state".
On the basis of this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner there are the good citizens, who are called Fermione, and follow the Pauli principle politely.
And in the other, the bosons, an evil band of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure, these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature are spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" that is the "bender" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" precisely at this location, in such a way as a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" to show this boson.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the exciter must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be feared by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is needed – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold itself in the refrigerator.
And similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while others (like the photon by the way) do not have a mass.
What can all these researches be “good for,” asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they serve to check the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to accurately examine all the deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who most eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great flaws, since it does not provide an explanation for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, no such deviations have been found at CERN so far.
Impacts
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be no.
By the way, in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in Bell Laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle – who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 – has already told us that the laser was initially regarded as a “laboratory.”
Imagine yourself...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, in 1969 Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its committee on "Death in Dignity", Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed soon, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that killed him had left him a two-year period.
“They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years,” he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in his home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
“However, it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an immense weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he reluctantly resigns to help himself with the meal.
Bravely, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to heal my diarrhea, because it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
“In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is pink while standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois’ home.
Returning to the childhood stage is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
“It depends on the person’s ability to take a step back,” he notes.
In the opinion of several people working in palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and through torture.”
But through the illness, I really got to know my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I have no more wishes in life,” she says, before accepting that you put on a mask that helps her breathe.
In the next few days, she still expects a final visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers are offered body care and food intake assistance.
Palliative care is then used when there are no other options.
To make the dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 residents.
That is very little, given that one day we will all die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or Pepsi as desired.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning, his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help family members and patients alike,” says nursing director Nathalie Savard.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, one day is not like the other.
In addition to a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family gathering in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, as one approaches his honour, a 36-year-old man who has been surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies after being carried around by everything, according to his will.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the home of Victor-Gadbois come from their place of residence, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter has reached the end of their lives, either at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Montreal Society for Home Palliative Care, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care system that ensures that several doctors specializing in palliative care are careful to ignore the adoption of a law to regulate the death penalty and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by prominent figures of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to declare their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to a high-quality palliative care before being accepted to switch to death support.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without taking measures to relieve her.
I fear that the patients just want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients despite the worst prognosis until the last day.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued a deplorable chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to cancel the treatment, she replied that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die are grateful to the care staff that this desire has not occurred after their pain has been alleviated by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at Montreal’s home palliative care company, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which tends to put the patient to sleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer act as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated, all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to fall asleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
