In addition, as is often the case with these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the belief that the current monetary system, shaped by banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible in dollars, euros, etc.) as well as a protocol for secure exchange such as BitTorrent, which allows the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers in the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
Some thousands of websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After the price of Bitcoin reached a peak of $30 (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>23) in June 2011, it fell to $2 five months later, before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as “the virtual currency with the greatest success”, “competition with the dollar or euro” and “similar to the traditional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through gaming (and sometimes even exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, each time the trade is controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the ledger, examiners, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public account book distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and distinct electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay with the same money twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) for fraud, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains unconnected, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be shared up to a hundred million, which leaves a certain amount of space...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement of the computing power.
The life of the network has already had highs and lows.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who just introduced Paymium, which is a real-money payment company and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse to donate this type.
They are accepted by others such as the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the bill and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a “mega-completion sale” was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are thus cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented with the dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend to be seen in which hierarchical systems are covered in favour of more horizontally oriented systems.
“It’s going to take some time for Bitcoin to get through, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he forecasts.
By the way, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks that are considered high today in the event of a success of this currency.
