A Constitution with the Breaker's Rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt, with regard to the declaration of the Constitution, which temporarily grants it unlimited power, remains more than ever divided, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just one week ago, the head of state granted this plenum two additional months for the completion of his work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has relied on a provisional, multiple-changed text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his “autocratic delirium” by continuing to “break his word” and “the right comes with its feet”.
On the side of its proponents, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to abandon their plan to explain to the Egyptians the text section by section.
For the president, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is raging across the country.
According to confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolent.
In particular, the Egyptian people, with this backlash, will be given an ultimatum to an overriding vote: "You either agree with my draft or I retain the unlimited power of authority", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals did not comply with the call.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt that they had not been able to enforce their views.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
In order to reach the decision-making capacity, 11 persons, deputy members, were added in all haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were usually unanimously adopted.
By the way, the commentators found it amusing that the only difference of opinion of the day... in the time for prayer came to be expressed, as some members of the committee were of the opinion that the pendulum of the Constituent Assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention, finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
“Sinfulness” is the response of the Liberals, who only see this as a propaganda blow.
They believe that the Islamicization of the Constitution is based on other articles.
They have in particular Article 220 in mind, which recognises an advisory function of the University of Al-Azhar, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is alarming because “the people who are called upon to make an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the first signs of a theocracy here."
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be far less moderate than the current one.
“There is currently no concrete religious commitment to be recognized.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who have been partly trained in the French system", explains Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, he concedes, "that there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, Am. d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticized for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the military's wishes, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no prohibition of civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations have demanded to defend human rights.
The latter also share their fears about the text, which they see as a threat to freedom.
The existence of blasphemy will be maintained, and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to free expression of opinion, especially for the press.
Furthermore, there is no longer any article on the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march up on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of sunshine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons for visiting Israel.
To bow before the holy places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It means that all who bathe in this river will receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, the walking on the water, the setting of the lake storm and the catch of fish.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the temples are located in Jerusalem.
Here believers follow the path of suffering or the way of the cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The road begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, in the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree grew from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the holiest place of the Jews - the walls of the prosecution, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave cards with wishes, which then go into fulfillment.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at an altitude of 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings an air cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the mountain top.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be allowed a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There are preserved ancient qumran manuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea found in rock caves in the Jewish Desert, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There is a collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the Museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most striking department is the monument for the children, which was built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room, there is complete darkness.
The stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and of the countries where they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do something for your health
The three main recreation areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 <0xC2><0xB0>C and the air warms up to 23 <0xC2><0xB0>C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salt content and thus even carries non-swimming smoothly on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is undescribedly beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt solstice) and healing mud as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of stressed nerves.
Touching the secrets of old age
These secrets lie in the old city of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous Seaway, Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia were connected.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to wander through the narrow streets named after the star sign.
Fortuna is supposed to be the legend after all who touch the walls in the street with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can wander through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman rulers, including Pontius Pilate.
Today evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Brand list for tourists
If you drive to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is preferred not in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged into tokens (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 tokens).
In the city you usually get on the bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed tram and in Haifa the only subway line of the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
To be precise, it is an underground cable car.
A ride within the city costs, regardless of the means of transport, 6 shekels, which is enough including a changeover for a ride of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is quiet.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without shells and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have a choice between different dishes with ham and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of peppered beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-bred cats that roam the streets comfortably and inexorably.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
Cats like busy places and don’t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shillings per day.
Admission tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shillings.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, which corresponds to an increase of 51% compared to the 2010 comparison period, before the lifting of the visa requirement on February 9, 2011.
‘The Great and Powerful’ Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with forged certificates
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Your only goal is to make money for the maintenance of the families that remain in the home.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every migrant must take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in retail.
However, the tests are expected to become mandatory for all guest workers in the future, according to the Federal Migration Agency.
Not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be proven for both the retention and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this Act are persons who have received their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The entire examination centres will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of People’s Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Citizens’ rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law entered into force in the press: What does the whole thing really bring?
What changes does the rule to have to show language skills, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
In particular, contrary to the Migration Agency's spokesman, it is a matter of reducing the number of forced laborers.
“Many are now talking about protecting the rights of working migrants,” says Viktor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical evaluation are facing problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who put him under the pretense of help in a dark, narrow barracks where he will endure with dozens of his equal months without food and documents and will be created 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have received many complaints from our migrants.
“In the home you will be promised the One, and upon arrival you will be deceived, get their passports taken off and not receive the promised salary,” confirms the head of the labor migration administration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripow.
Don't be shy, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they can hardly express themselves in writing, not only in the language of the target country.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable basic education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
“It’s difficult without language skills,” they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
The following important aspects of the law are highlighted by civil rights advocates.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to remain illegal in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Prohibited access for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that our documents are for the most part forged and we are not registered, and this then results in cases of blackmail.
“They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea,” the Tajik Umed Huschkadamow told reporters.
"Don't waste any money on fake papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be forged.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive this for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself thus the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs one migrant three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased, both officials and civil servants agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will receive time for a language basic course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered positions in areas where no active understanding with people is necessary.
Home Ministry Ignores Illegal Arms Market
The share of legal weapons in crimes is extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning to tighten the gun law for private gun owners.
In response, the authorities responded to the latest events: Injured in shootings at weddings, as well as seven dead in the seizure of Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradow.
The police want to ban the use of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be tabled soon.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "drawing the screws".
On the Internet, an open letter was published, whose author – representatives of various arms associations – is urging the authorities to distance themselves from “senseless intensifications.”
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, the criminal justice official, Vasily Lesnikov, told the BBC’s Russian service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes using registered weapons were committed over the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using themselves on the black market.
At present, according to the authors, in Moscow you can find any weapon for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from the factories to the officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,” Baranez said.
On the second channel there are illegal weapons, which are stolen by law-enforcement guards from criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons that were stolen from both the police’s weapons chambers and directly from employees of law enforcement agencies.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Explosions have often occurred in many military camps.
“There is evidence that in some cases it was a fire foundation to cover up the lack of weapons,” said the former military official.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition, and that is why the weapons are hand in hand on the black market, for example in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
In particular, many guns and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a separate, sometimes artisanal production, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling,” explains the former military official.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated what proportion each of the five channels has in the supply of the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on the topic of weapons.
According to investigators, the majority of illegal weapons come from the army and the law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market were there because of the “guilty of responsible people who have come to grips with weapons in their work,” the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict areas, 14% go back to theft in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
