Poland and Space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the member countries of the European Space Agency, making it the second member country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The journey of Poland into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish space enthusiasts engaged in space travel, thus not always coming to terms with it.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the REP Hirsch prize, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and spaceflight.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s world-renowned contribution to the development of space travel was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the Earth-facing side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway draisin was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not yet clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to brake the draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-propelled guns.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the submitted documents, it is evident that the research was advanced to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then freely interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the specialist press published the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket by Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpedoa powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work his work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on spaceflight appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Agency (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautzycky) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company takes place in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles on space travel are devoted.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space society.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be expected that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Agency (PTA) attempted to join the International Federation for Spaceflight, founded in 1951, and in fact, the PTA became a regular member already in the fall of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became deputy chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh as much as 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 began flight tests with the two-stage RM-2 rocket in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed approximately 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
However, in 1962 the further development was discontinued.
The first rocket of the RM type was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differ in size from each other in the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight altitude for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aviation, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek.
The repeal of the Law on Non-Profits is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court lifted the law on non-profit works.
This decision raised a lively debate in the public eye.
It is certainly interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
The liberalised economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in a permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with relentless financial speculations.
Due to the large differences in the value of labor (wage) there are price tensions.
Under this concept is to be understood a condition in which the manufacturer attempts to prevail in economic competition through the import of advantageous goods by "inviting" the competition, thereby tearing a larger market share into itself and increasing its profit.
On a large scale, this means for most companies moving their production abroad or shopping there cheaply, or giving up their business. The result is high unemployment in countries with comparable high labour costs.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment caused by it, state expenditures necessarily increase.
This situation is further exacerbated by the fact that employers are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the overall economic and social damage caused by them.
This situation is generally known, so that concrete statistics are superfluous at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates in the individual economies a situation in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thereby attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver their own people to private capital without regard to the social consequences.
This is reflected, in particular, in changes to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the own population to accept the dictatorship of private capital, in particular in the wage area.
This is done, on the one hand, by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, and, on the other hand, by the reduction of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, for several years now, there have been public food rations for poor people who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regular cases in which workers receive such low wages that the state has to raise their income to the minimum of existence.
Such a scandal was also discovered in the case of auxiliaries employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU southern countries will undoubtedly end up in the same state in which people are forced to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level, or that they will be forced to work and invest in private wages on the margins of society.
The question is, of course, where does this capital come from?
When it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or the capital remains the same, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or Africa, the workers work for a fraction of the European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media claim to the extreme that the state is not allowed to participate with capital in its own economy, and that planning economics leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists strongly on its position that the state should not interfere with the economy.
Then one has to wonder whether private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the whole state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer: Yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a practically omnipotent and omnipresent lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, mutual benefit, a legislation in which practically everything is punishable, but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that a Ministry of State mandates private law firms, which are closely intertwined with the industry, to draft legislation.
These bills will then be passed in the Bundestag.
All violence is then no longer based on the people, as the Western constitutions declare, but on strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Obviously, liberal democracies are now quickly entering a situation, as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic at the time of Caesar and Pompey': "The state had long been in decay, and the offices were filled with violence.
Against lubricants, by unlawful simplification of advantages or with stone and sword.
The corruption grew unhindered, and the people went to the election with already bought votes" ... "people with character do not compete for office, so that the state did not have a consul for eight months as a result of this downfall" ... "The people were really starting to talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult manor was
As it turns out, today’s society, as in ancient times, is based on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital, by its very nature, is not able to recognize and enforce the advantage for the whole society.
The result, now and then, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites who do not at all strive for deeper reforms.
We must therefore look for the cause of the rise of fascism and communism in the ruthless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today's point of view, the downfall of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain break, which already marks the next round.
Especially catastrophic is the fact that the elites of today are completely ignorant of the possible loss of hundreds of thousands of lives in the future, the humanitarian and social catastrophes of which we are already witnesses today, and the crimes against humanity, as we know them from the past and recent history.
The repeal of the Law on Non-Profits is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under pressure from global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to push the social level of the population down.
This trend is therefore system-related.
The only solution is targeted political and social reforms that increase the state’s capital participation in the economy, increase citizens’ influence on the government, and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society in favor of the state.
