The film Argo: When It's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the fallen Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had guarded the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the U.S. government, there was no positive way out of this situation – it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent failure of the violent attempt to free the hostages only made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages brought home a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six embassy workers managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian Ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran; helping them hide their true identity – they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly filmed in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also made Hollywood's collaboration necessary.
To make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in professional magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Husar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence are shown iconic contemporary photographs, and even in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which are ironically and slightly overrated therefore come.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the office floor, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has achieved a remarkable start to his career with this film.
From a smiling actor he has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the Crimi No Child's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film, which does not play in the director’s home Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place was one of the hallmarks of this director’s previous films from Standard Hollywood.
Affleck, however, also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the incoming sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet still conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story takes place.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck and his team in fictional scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story actually does not offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality a little bit - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is diverted from a phone call in America, or even the pursuit on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its all-too-wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, and thus they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film thus loses a bit of traction, a film that can be followed with a certain interest, while tasting the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70s.
However, it only arouses enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history alive to this day, and as proof of how the ideas of the all-powerful and all-knowing intelligence agencies are covered, it is sufficient.
