Yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) does not see this.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
The walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti of boredom, dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea before a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of wanting to "exercise a satisfying activity, but not being able to".
Apathy is therefore different from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
Apathy, on the other hand, is not an urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, exists in a "disruption of the attention process, coupled with bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly".
Being bored can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two states might be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re boring, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German, for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Procrastination from the Point of Attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", a scholar points to Professor Eastwood and his colleague
Some groups listened to a loud TV show from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others listened to it at low volume, so it was hardly noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who took the barely audible television reported feeling more boredom than the other two groups — they had trouble concentrating, couldn’t find a reason for it, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
If you try to focus on a difficult or stressful task, the distraction can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a monotonous activity - "just like searching for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that heresy and riddles, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even combat them by keeping people physically more alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to wander around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point — my late flight, a buzzing loudspeaker, a particularly exhausting movie.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
In order to measure these differences, researchers in the 1980s developed a "scale to long-term susceptibility".
On the scale are statements such as "many things I have to do are repeated and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida – particularly regarding the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty strained bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adults were bored in school and doing homework, while 23% said they would be bored if they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know if the percentages in terms of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is confident that “youth will feel particularly boring,” mainly because children and teenagers don’t have much influence on their daily lives.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it leads to people taking extreme physical risks and dropping the gambling or drugs to relieve them - this has been shown by studies.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors are investigating the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else,” said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
If you are bored and you use this energy to play guitar and cook, you will be happy.
But television can provide short-term feelings of happiness, but these are fleeting in the long-term.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, it can take it away from boredom, but it has not learned to entertain or control itself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: “Self-control transfers itself from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to entertain himself, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
We should also not see them too critical.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant activity and technology boom.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the patient, unceasing desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
He believes that people in truth are only looking for a way to turn off and relax.
