Larry Hagman was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, and became famous worldwide for his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series "Dallas", where he played a ruthless, secretive and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the greed of the 1980s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. this year in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday afternoon from cancer complications, according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked most," the family said.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving celebration.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died in the Dallas hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He made everyone who knew him happy.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original person and lived life in full swing,” Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted drinking a lot over the years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver, and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas", Hagman became known on television as a nice guy between 1965 and 1970 with the sitcom "Beautiful Jeannie" of the NBC television station.
There he played the astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is put on his head when he meets an attractive "Dshinn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live with him at home.
He was also an actor in two short-lived comedies, such as "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971–72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the charmingly despicable J.R. that made Hagman a superstar.
The drama series of the CBS television series about the Ewing Clan and other characters in its surroundings was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The commercial "Who Shot J.R.?", which was supposed to create the expectation of an episode full of emotions, where the character of Hagmann was almost killed, led to international speculation, and millions of dollars were wagered in betting houses.
The series reached a viewership record at the time.
